<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Credit default swaps have two related function=
s:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You can trade CDS to bet on the credi=
tworthiness of some company (or country, or type of structured credit, etc.=
). When the company reports good earnings or otherwise seems to be more cre=
ditworthy, its CDS price will go down, and people who sold CDS will have a =
mark-to-market gain. When the company reports bad earnings or otherwise see=
ms to be falling apart, its CDS price will go up, and people who bought CDS=
 will have a mark-to-market gain.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
CDS works as insurance against default. If the company (country, pool of lo=
ans, etc.) defaults on its debt, then CDS is =E2=80=9Ctriggered,=E2=80=9D t=
he people who sold CDS have to pay some money to the people who bought CDS,=
 and there is some fairly complex <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/33044024.256428/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9=
uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDQtMTAvaG92bmFuaWFuLXMtd2VpcmQtY2RzLXRyYWRlLWdldHMtd2=
VpcmRlcj9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDE2MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb=
3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEwMTYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc4a16c08" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  auction process</a> to determi=
ne how much.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Thing 1=C2=A0<em>sort of=C2=A0</em>works by ba=
ckward induction from=C2=A0Thing 2: As the creditworthiness of the issuer g=
oes down, it becomes more likely that the CDS will trigger, which makes it =
more likely that CDS sellers will have to pay CDS buyers, and in broad stro=
kes the auction process in Thing 2 means that the sellers pay buyers more t=
he worse things end up being for the issuer.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that is approximate, and these things are =
not=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>tightly coupled. The actual payout mechanism, u=
pon a default, is not simply =E2=80=9Cthe CDS pays more the worse the defau=
lt is.=E2=80=9D In fact there might be an auction with different deliverabl=
e securities, and there can be a certain amount of gamesmanship in the auct=
ion, and there are various ways to affect the result to make the payout hig=
her or lower than you might intuitively expect. We <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33044024.256428/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDQtMTAvaG92bmFuaWFuLXMtd2VpcmQtY2RzL=
XRyYWRlLWdldHMtd2VpcmRlcj9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDE2MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVt=
PWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzEwMTYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWd=
uPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCc4a16c08" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talk</a> from=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33044024.256428/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMTEtMjgvc2Vh=
cnMtZGVmYXVsdC1iZXRzLXBheS1vZmYtZm9yLXNlYXJzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMTYyM19NT05FWVN=
UVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMT=
AxNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe1b3d399" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">  time</a> to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/33044024.256428/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS92aWV3L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMT=
gtMDUtMDEvYW5vdGhlci13ZWlyZC1kZWFsLXVwc2V0cy1jZHMtdHJhZGVycz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxM=
DE2MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1=
dG1fdGVybT0yMzEwMTYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cBb985dc1a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">  time</a> around here about companies or investors buy=
ing or creating or hoarding or releasing securities in order to get the pri=
ce of the auction closer to what they want. The outcomes can get weird. A c=
ompany that collapses in a pile of rubble could have CDS that pays off zero=
 cents on the dollar; a company that is basically fine could do a technical=
 default and have CDS that pays off 100 cents on the dollar.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Broadly speaking, CDS is a generic bet on the =
issuer=E2=80=99s creditworthiness=C2=A0<em>as long as it isn=E2=80=99t too =
close to default</em>, but it is a hyperspecific bet on auction mechanics a=
nd deliverable securities and intra-creditor game theory when the issuer is=
 in default.=C2=A0And there is a transition zone where, as the issuer=E2=80=
=99s credit gets worse, people who=C2=A0<em>were=C2=A0</em>reading the issu=
er=E2=80=99s financial statements to bet on its business=C2=A0have to switc=
h over to start reading its bond documents to bet on the mechanics.=C2=A0</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so if you buy CDS on some issuer as a bet =
against its economic fundamentals, and those fundamentals deteriorate, then=
 the price of CDS will go up and you will have a big paper gain on your bet=
, because you are still in the zone where the CDS acts as a bet on fundamen=
tals. Perhaps you should sell your CDS and take your profits! Or you can ho=
ld on, but as the fundamentals get even worse, they will also get less impo=
rtant, and the dark arts of CDS auction mechanics will become more importan=
t.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a Wall Street Journal=C2=A0<a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33044024.256428/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9maW5hbmNlL2ludmVzdGluZy9jYXJsLWljYWhuLWJldC1vbi10aGUtY=
mlnLXNob3J0LTItMC1ub3ctaGUtc2F5cy10aGUtZ2FtZS13YXMtcmlnZ2VkLTFjZTA5MGFhP21v=
ZD1pdHBfd3Nq/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB62258876" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">story about Carl Ic=
ahn</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Four years ago, legendary Wall Street investor=
 Carl Icahn made a huge bet against the future of the U.S. shopping mall in=
 what was called the Big Short 2.0. His wager pitted him against huge asset=
 managers and hedge funds that routinely deal in a notoriously complex and =
contentious market. =C2=A0 =C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bet used credit-default swaps, essentially=
 insurance policies insuring bonds against losses, tied to an index trackin=
g bundles of loans to malls and other commercial properties. Purchasers pay=
 a monthly premium, but the policies can pay out potentially huge sums if t=
he bonds take a loss. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, Icahn, 87 years old, is watching some of =
his jackpot slip away. In 2022, Icahn Enterprises=E2=80=99 credit-default s=
wap positions took a $742 million paper loss, according to corporate filing=
s, and the firm=E2=80=99s short credit positions have also been losers so f=
ar in 2023. Adding insult to injury: When Crossgates [Mall]=E2=80=99s debt =
recently sold for nearly $100 million less than its previous value, the pri=
ce was just high enough to avoid triggering a payout on some derivatives Ic=
ahn used to bet against malls.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He now claims this twist shows the deck was st=
acked against him by his trading counterparties, though veterans caution th=
at markets like this one are rife with disputes of this sort.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIn many instances, it=E2=80=99s just =
a rigged market for billions and billions of dollars,=E2=80=9D Icahn said i=
n an interview.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Icahn bet against the CMBX 6, an index of comm=
ercial mortgage-backed securities that was heavily weighted toward risky sh=
opping malls, in 2019. It worked out great:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When Covid-19 hit the following year, the inde=
x crashed and the value of its derivative CDS contracts surged. Some other =
funds shorting the CMBX 6 sold out of positions for big profits, while Icah=
n=E2=80=99s positions gained about $900 million for the year.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Icahn increased the size of his bet, according=
 to financial filings.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CA lot of these bonds now are in grave=
 danger,=E2=80=9D Icahn told CNBC. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s like selling insur=
ance to someone who=E2=80=99s going to go to the electric chair in a couple=
 of months.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then loans to Crossgates Mall defaulted in=
 May 2023, and they were sold at auction, and =E2=80=9Cthe servicer receive=
d a stalking horse offer of $162 million from a small Connecticut hedge fun=
d called Cannae Portfolio Advisors,=E2=80=9D $40 million higher than the ne=
xt bid and =E2=80=9Cjust enough to ensure that one of the three Crossgates =
securitizations would avoid losses that would trigger a CDS payout tied to =
certain tranches of the debt.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Icahn bet that mall debt would perform poorly,=
 and it did, and he made money. And then he kept the bet on, and increased =
it. But meanwhile the bet itself shifted: It was no longer a bet that mall =
debt would perform poorly; it was now a bet on how an auction for one parti=
cular loan would clear. It stopped being a bet on macroeconomic conditions,=
 and became a bet on a poker game. He should have gotten out while he was s=
till right.</p>
