<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At a very high level, the way banking works is=
:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">People have money and would like to e=
arn interest on it.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They put the m=
oney in the bank, which lends it to other people, who do stuff =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0run businesses, buy houses =E2=80=94=C2=A0with the money and pay interes=
t to the bank.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">This funds economic=
 activity, and over time, the economy mostly grows. There are more people, =
more productivity, more stuff. If I take $100 from you and use it to buy a =
house or start a business, and I promise to pay you back $110 with the proc=
eeds of my house or business, there=E2=80=99s a pretty good chance that I w=
ill be able to do that, that the thing I buy now will be worth more later. =
I invest the $100 in productive enterprises, those productive enterprises p=
ay off $120, I pay back the loan with interest and have $10 left over for m=
yself.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Obviously sometimes this do=
esn=E2=80=99t work =E2=80=94=C2=A0my business fails, my neighborhood gets c=
heaper =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the successes should outweigh the failures, and i=
f banks are diversified and well capitalized they=E2=80=99ll be fine and ca=
n pay back their depositors.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Occas=
ionally the whole system overreaches =E2=80=94=C2=A0all the banks decide, a=
t once, to bet all their money on home prices going up =E2=80=94=C2=A0and t=
he bet goes wrong and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/33044024.256428/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvTWluc2t5X21vbWV=
udA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB68bcb6ce" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> there=E2=80=99s a financial=
 crisis</a>.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Broadly, banking is a=C2=A0<em>levered bet on =
economic growth</em>, and the bet is risky but usually pays off.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How does crypto banking work? I think there ar=
e three broad ways to conceive of it:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=9CCrypto=E2=80=9D and=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9Cbanking=E2=80=9D simply don=E2=80=99t go together. The strict view of=
 some early crypto adopters is that crypto is an=C2=A0<em>alternative=C2=A0=
</em>to the leverage of traditional banking. Traditional banks hold your mo=
ney for you and use it to make levered bets on economic growth, and that is=
 risky, and if you don=E2=80=99t like it you can use crypto. You hold your =
money for yourself, nobody is making any bets with it, everything is transp=
arent and on the blockchain, there are no intermediaries, there is no hidde=
n leverage or risk of financial crisis. It feels quaint to me to even type =
this, but I think this view was pretty influential in the early days of cry=
pto.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Crypto banking is just like r=
egular banking, a levered bet on economic growth: There are crypto firms, q=
uasi-banks, that hold people=E2=80=99s cryptocurrency=C2=A0for them and pay=
 them interest, and they use that crypto to invest in productive enterprise=
s that grow the economy and return enough to pay the interest. They lend ou=
t crypto to people who want to start businesses or buy homes or open factor=
ies. Anything is possible! I know from experience that if I write =E2=80=9C=
you don=E2=80=99t hear much about people borrowing crypto to start real-wor=
ld businesses=C2=A0or buy houses,=E2=80=9D someone will email me to say =E2=
=80=9CI have a firm that lets people borrow crypto to buy houses on the blo=
ckchain.=E2=80=9D But =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I mean =E2=80=A6=C2=A0not=C2=A0<em>so=
=C2=A0</em>much?</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Crypto banking is=
 purely financial, a levered bet=C2=A0<em>on the size of the crypto market<=
/em>. There are crypto firms, quasi-banks, that hold people=E2=80=99s crypt=
ocurrency for them and pay them interest, and they use that crypto to inves=
t in more crypto. They lend out crypto to hedge funds that want to make lev=
ered bets on crypto, and as long as crypto prices generally go up those hed=
ge funds will make enough money to pay back the loans with interest and get=
 rich themselves. But=C2=A0<em>nothing productive is happening=C2=A0</em>wi=
th these money flows; people are buying tokens but not doing any activity t=
hat makes anyone better off in the real world. Crypto prices go up because =
people=C2=A0speculate on crypto, so there is more money in crypto, so it is=
 easier to borrow more money to make more levered bets on crypto, so prices=
 keep going up, etc., until a slight breeze blows it all over and there=E2=
=80=99s nothing left.</li>
</ol>
